text.tspan: Clients should not be forced to depend on functions they do

g.title: Folded Corner.73
g.desc: Developers introducing new modules can be confused by unrelat...

g.text: Developers introducing new modules can be confused by unrelated functionality within an interface definition. It can be hard for both the using as the implementing side to understand the rationale. This often results in more time spent in investigating and expanding the knowledge on the current fix or feature.

g.title: Folded Corner.83
g.desc: A result of small, cohesive interfaces is that less ‘implemen...

g.text: A result of small, cohesive interfaces is that less ‘implementing’ clients are dependent on the same interface. This means that less clients are affected when we do need to introduce an interface change. This then results in less maintenance, resulting in a lower time commitment and reduces the chance of introducing bugs.

g.title: Folded Corner.58
g.desc: Clients implementing and using one ‘bulky’ interface will res...

g.text: Clients implementing and using one ‘bulky’ interface will result in recompilation of all clients when an interface change is required. Introducing more cohesive and smaller interfaces means we have less clients dependent on the same interface. Introducing a change in the interface will have less impact. In large systems this could save time during re-compilation.

g.title: Rectangle.85
g.desc: Overcome ‘using’ clients to handle unimplemented interfaces
g.text: Overcome ‘using’ clients to handle unimplemented interfaces

g.title: Folded Corner.86
g.desc: The side-effect of the ‘implementing’ client not fully implem...

g.text: The side-effect of the ‘implementing’ client not fully implementing the interface is that the ‘using clients’ often have to be modified as well (e.g. try-catch constructions or checks for the concrete type). In contrast adhering to ISP, the design and time commitment improves, because we don’t need ‘handling mechanisms’ for these ‘unimplemented’ use cases.

g.title: Rectangle.92
g.desc: Overcome forcedly updating clients that don’t ‘need’ the comp...
g.text: Overcome forcedly updating clients that don’t ‘need’ the complete interface

g.title: Folded Corner.96
g.desc: A low cohesive interface, meaning an interface with unrelated...

g.text: A low cohesive interface, meaning an interface with unrelated functionality, can result in the ‘implementing’ client not being able to fully implement this interface. The result is that we have to spent time on ‘making up’ and maintaining some implementation for these unused functions (e.g. throwing an ‘unimplemented’ exception). In contrast when adhering to ISP, less time is spent on interface changes, less chance of introducing bugs (e.g. unhandled exceptions or unforeseen behavior) and we clarify our design intent.

g.title: Rectangle.105
g.desc: Less re-testing and fixing test cases
g.text: Less re-testing and fixing test cases

g.title: Folded Corner.107
g.desc: A client, not able to fully implement a certain interface, co...

g.text: A client, not able to fully implement a certain interface, could potentially return a null pointer. The ‘using’ client could dereference this null pointer and break the program. This means the ‘using’ client has to implement a check (if-condition) to see if the returning value is not null. This increases the cyclomatic complexity of the program.

g.title: Folded Corner.114
g.desc: A ‘implementing’ client, not able to fully implement a certai...

g.text: A ‘implementing’ client, not able to fully implement a certain interface, will contain redundant code (e.g. returning null or exceptions). This redundant code will decrease readability and thus increase complexity of the system.

g.title: Folded Corner.124
g.desc: The interfaces we are declaring are small and cohesive, when ...

g.text: The interfaces we are declaring are small and cohesive, when we adhere to ISP. This enlarges the chance of an existing interface fitting a new use case. There is less time spent on redefining, understanding and handling redundant interface functions.

g.title: Folded Corner.85
g.desc: When adhering to ISP the ‘using’ clients only obtain the inte...

g.text: When adhering to ISP the ‘using’ clients only obtain the interface they need. This will result in smaller, dependency interfaces. This means we spent less time mocking and we can identify failures earlier. In contrast, violating ISP, means we have to spent time mocking interfaces functions the ‘using’ client does not use!

g.title: Folded Corner.132
g.desc: Retesting will be needed in case the ‘using’ client doesn’t u...

g.text: Retesting will be needed in case the ‘using’ client doesn’t use the full interface of its dependencies and a change is introduced in one of these unused functions. We have to adjust our mocks to the interface change and retest. In contrast, when adhering to ISP, the client is only dependent on the functions its uses. Unrelated functionality will not affect our test cases and no re-testing is required.

g.title: Folded Corner.140
g.desc: ISP constraints the ‘using’ client to only use the necessary ...

g.text: ISP constraints the ‘using’ client to only use the necessary sub-set of the public accessible functions a module has. The added value is that we can control our system into correct behavior and overcome bugs. The ‘using’ client only gets the interface to the functions it needs. Martin Fowler calls this ‘role’ interfaces.

g.title: Folded Corner.102
g.desc: Applying ISP to the extreme would mean a single function per ...

g.text: Applying ISP to the extreme would mean a single function per interface. This would result in a scattered code base, which is hard to maintain. There should be balance. Looking from the ‘using’ client perspective often can help us with grouping cohesive interface functions.

g.title: Folded Corner.153
g.desc: The ‘using’ clients often tell us a lot about the interfaces ...

g.text: The ‘using’ clients often tell us a lot about the interfaces we should compose. We should introduce new interfaces or reconsider the interfaces in case the ‘using’ client does not use the complete interface of its dependencies.

g.title: Folded Corner.162
g.desc: We can apply the adapter pattern in case the existing code ha...

g.text: We can apply the adapter pattern in case the existing code has ISP violations. A new module we introduce doesn’t need the low cohesive, ‘bulky’ interface a dependency provide. The adapter pattern makes it possible to wrap the ISP ‘violating’ dependency into a fitting interface.

g.title: Rectangle.171
g.desc: Increasing complexity when introducing too many interfaces
g.text: Increasing complexity when introducing too many interfaces

g.title: Folded Corner.173
g.desc: In-case ISP is taken to the ‘extreme’ we will end up with a s...

g.text: In-case ISP is taken to the ‘extreme’ we will end up with a scattered code base. A lot of single function interfaces will make it hard to navigate through the code, decrease readability and overcomplicate dependency injection in case grouping of interfaces is not applied.
